# .security-audit-allowlist
#
# Substring patterns matched against file paths. One pattern per line.
# Lines starting with # and blank lines are ignored.
#
# CURRENT MECHANISM IS FILE-LEVEL ONLY — silencing a file silences ALL
# findings in it, current and future. Per-finding allowlisting (file +
# category + detail-substring) is captured as BTS-152 and would make
# this affordance more precise.
#
# Each entry MUST include a comment explaining why the file is allowlisted
# and what review surface still covers it.

# settings.json contains absolute path patterns (e.g., Read(//Users/...))
# that flag as PII because of the username segment. Permissions in this
# file are independently reviewed via permissions-audit.sh; the security
# audit's PII scan is redundant for permission entries by design.
# Origin: BTS-142 autonomy-first permissions rewrite.
# Per-finding granularity: BTS-152 (when shipped, switch this entry to a
# detail-substring pattern targeting only PII-in-permission entries).
.claude/settings.json
